problems.problem_statement:
Background:  

Consider a digital memcomputing machine (DMM) designed to solve 3-SAT instances with $N$ logical variables $v_n\in[-1,1]$ and $M$ clauses. Each clause $m$ contains exactly three logical variables, which we denote (for clause $m$) as $(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m})$. For any clause $m$ containing logical variable $v_n$, we denote the other two logical variables in that clause as $v_{j}$ and $v_{k}$. Each clause $m$ is also associated with two types of memory variables: a short-term memory $x_m^s\in[0,1]$ and a long-term memory $x_m^l$. Logical variables are initialized randomly, $x_m^s(0)=1/2$, and $x_m^l(0)=1$. The dynamics are governed by the following coupled ordinary differential equations for all $n$ and $m$:
\begin{align*}
    \dot{v}_n &= \sum_{m\in S(n)} x_m^l x_m^s\,G_{n,m}(v_n, v_j, v_k) + \sum_{m\in S(n)} (1+\zeta x_m^l)(1-x_m^s)\,R_{n,m}(v_n, v_j, v_k), \\
    \dot{x}_m^s &= \beta [C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}) - \gamma], \\
    \dot{x}_m^l &= \begin{cases} \alpha[C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}) - \delta], &\text{if } C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}) \geq \delta \\ \alpha[C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m})-\delta](x_m^l-1), &\text{if } C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}) < \delta \end{cases}
\end{align*}
where $\alpha, \beta, \gamma, \delta, \zeta$ are fixed parameters. For each clause $m$, $S(n)$ denotes the set of clauses containing the variable $v_n$. For each such clause, $(v_n, v_j, v_k)$ are the three variables in the clause, with $v_n$ explicitly given and $v_j$ and $v_k$ denoting the other two variables in the same clause. The functions within each clause $m$ are defined by:
\begin{align*}
    G_{n,m}(v_n, v_j, v_k) &= \frac{1}{2} q_{n,m}\min[(1 - q_{j,m} v_j), (1 - q_{k,m} v_k)] \\
    R_{n,m}(v_n, v_j, v_k) &= 
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{1}{2}q_{n,m}(1 - q_{n,m} v_n), & \text{if } C_m(v_n, v_j, v_k) = \frac{1}{2}(1 - q_{n,m}v_n)\\
        0, & \text{otherwise}
    \end{cases} \\
    C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}) &= \frac{1}{2}\min[(1 - q_{i_m}v_{i_m}), (1 - q_{j_m}v_{j_m}), (1 - q_{k_m}v_{k_m})]
\end{align*}
with $q_{l,m}\in\{\pm 1\}$ for $l=i_m, j_m, k_m$ encoding whether variable $v_l$ appears negated in clause $m$ ($+1$ for non-negated, $-1$ for negated). When using $C_m(v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m})$, $v_{i_m}, v_{j_m}, v_{k_m}$ are the three variables in clause $m$ according to its definition. When $C_m$ appears as an argument with other variables, it should be interpreted with respect to the variable arrangement in the specific clause $m$.

Task:

Starting from the above definitions and equations, derive, for arbitrary $n$, an explicit expression for $\dot{v}_n$ fully in terms of $v_n$, $v_j$, $v_k$, $x_m^s$, $x_m^l$, $\zeta$, and the $q_{l,m}$ for all clauses $m$ containing $v_n$. Your answer should be an explicit sum over clauses $m\in S(n)$ containing $v_n$, involving only the above quantities and no undefined functions.

