problems.problem_statement:
Background:  

Consider a metapopulation consisting of $\Omega$ demes, each with wild-type cells ($W$) and mutant cells ($M$). The fitnesses are $f_W=1$, $f_M=1+s$ with $0 < s \ll 1$. Each deme has a carrying capacity $K$, and all demes are arranged on a regular circulation graph $\mathrm{G}$ (such as a clique, cycle, or grid), with each deme connected to $q_{\mathrm{G}}$ nearest neighbors. Cells migrate independently of birth and death events: from any deme $x$, a cell of type $\alpha\in\{W,M\}$ can migrate to one of its $q_{\mathrm{G}}$ neighbors at per-capita rate $m$. In each deme, the intra-deme birth-death process follows: a cell of type $\alpha$ divides at rate $T^+_\alpha = (f_\alpha/\overline{f}) n_\alpha$ and dies at rate $T^-_\alpha = (n / K) n_\alpha$, with $n_\alpha$ the number of $\alpha$ cells and $n$ the total population in the deme; $\overline{f}=(n_Wf_W + n_Mf_M)/n$. Assume the metapopulation initially has $i$ demes entirely occupied by mutants, and $\Omega - i$ with only wild-type. In the regime of slow migration $(m \ll 1)$ and large carrying capacity ($K \gg 1$), deme extinction is negligible. An invasion occurs when a cell migrates to a neighboring deme and fixes there. 

The invasion probabilities for a single mutant into a wild deme and a single wild-type into a mutant deme are:
\[
\begin{aligned}
    \rho_{M}(K)&=\frac{1}{1+s}\frac{s}{1-(1+s)^{-K}}\\
    \rho_{W}(K)&=\frac{1}{(1+s)^{K}}\frac{s}{1-(1+s)^{-K}}
\end{aligned}
\]
The number of active edges (connections between $M$ demes and $W$ demes) is $E_{\mathrm{G}}(i)$, and the per-deme migration rate is $m K$. The coarse-grained stochastic dynamics for the number $i$ of mutant demes has transition rates:
\[
\begin{aligned}
    T^+_i &= m K \frac{E_{\mathrm{G}}(i)}{q_{\mathrm{G}}} \rho_{M}(K) \quad \text{(increase $i$ by $1$)} \\
    T^-_i &= m K \frac{E_{\mathrm{G}}(i)}{q_{\mathrm{G}}} \rho_{W}(K) \quad \text{(decrease $i$ by $1$)} 
\end{aligned}
\]
The process is absorbed if $i=0$ (all wild-type) or $i=\Omega$ (all mutant).

Task:

Given the above metapopulation and stochastic process, derive an explicit formula for the probability that the mutants eventually take over the entire metapopulation, starting from a single mutant deme ($i=1$), as a function of $s$, $K$, and $\Omega$. Your answer should be a closed-form function of $K$, $s$, and $\Omega$, and should not explicitly depend on the migration rate $m$ or the graph structure $\mathrm{G}$.

